AB  - This study explored the use of common formative assessments and their potential to increase student achievement in mathematics as measured by standardized tests. A problem of instructional reform in the United States has been to find and consistently apply a methodology pertinent to all school systems and grade levels that meets the objectives of the Elementary and Secondary Education Act of 2002, known as No Child Left Behind (NCLB), while also improving classroom instruction. Practices such as block scheduling, professional learning communities (PLCs), as well as instructional reform practices have been mandated by the federal government in order to meet its objectives for low-performing, Title-1 schools. One best practice recommended by NCLB is the use of common formative assessments. This study examined how students' standardized test scores in mathematics changed since the introduction of common formative assessments and how these changes compare with changes in test scores in the other core subject areas. This quantitative case study used a t-test, linear regression analysis, and ANOVA to compare achievement scores of 2 cohorts. One cohort participated in a school-wide common formative assessment practice aligned with the California Standards Test. The means of the 2 cohorts were compared to determine whether in-house common assessment scores positively correlated with students' California Standards Test scores. This study also inquired into the correlation between common formative assessments with regard to ethnicity and socioeconomic status, and the increased proficiency in mathematics as measured by the California Standards Test, a correlation relevant to all educators—particularly those school sites with a population of English Language Learners and students who qualify for free or reduced priced lunch. The findings of this study determined common formative assessments: (a) correlate positively with scores on the California Standards Test, (b) are vehicles that allow socioeconomically disadvantaged students to increase their performance on the California Standards Test, and (b) encourage teachers' to modify their instruction. In addition, the findings of this study supported a need to suggest improvements to the current program in order to increase the effectiveness of common formative assessments.
