AB  - The purpose of this study is to examine empirically the efficacy of using technology based formative evaluation procedures to provide instructional feedback and to determine its potential impact on students' learning, retention, forgetting, and rates of learning in urban classroom settings. The technology based formative evaluation assessment format used in this study is known in the literature as subjective probability assessment and is designed to measure student attainment on a two-dimensional scale. With this two-dimensional format the student is required to indicate both the choice of a correct response (recognition or competence) and the degree of sureness (confidence) that the student has in the choice. Hunt (1989) in his research found that the forgetting of previously learned information and the acquisition of new information can be greatly influenced by student confidence in information. Instructional feedback and training teachers in differential pedagogy depending upon student information quality are employed as part of the research design of this study. Misinformation, partial information and lack of information require the teacher to differentiate between the instructional strategies of remediation, review, and instruction. A pretest, posttest, post-posttest type of experimental design was used in this study to explore how this technology based formative evaluation procedure impacted on student learning, forgetting and possibly the rate of learning in mathematics. Ancillary data was also collected in an effort to examine if there was any correlation effect between student performance on the information referenced standard and the norm referenced mathematics test results that are administered by the school district. The results of the study revealed that learning is significantly enhanced with formative evaluation. Using an analysis of variance procedure and t-test methods the experimental group statistically outperformed the control group. Additionally, an analysis of norm referenced test data revealed that there was a strong correlation between the students' mathematics performance as measured by the formative evaluation procedure and the norm referenced testing that was administered by the school district. This indicates that the technology based, formative evaluation procedure can be used as an effective strategy for increasing student achievement and norm referenced test scores.
