AB  - Although JEMP (Jaime Escalante Math Program) is currently in its 35th year, research has yet to be conducted on confirming the program's claims for increased math scores. This study examined the impact of JEMP's Pre-Algebra and Algebra intervention courses on student math achievement in District A (Los Angeles County). Archived math scores for middle school students from 2010-2013 in District A were examined. JEMP instructors used the MDTP (Mathematics Diagnostic Testing Project) assessment to guide instruction by providing formative feedback on students' progress. They also administered the CST (California Standardized Test) to all students at the end of the academic school year. This study sought to (a) determine if the MDTP assessments could predict student achievement on the Pre-Algebra and Algebra California Standards Test (CST) and (b) determine if JEMP improves students' CST math scores. A nonexperimental multiple regression design was used to investigate the relationship between the MDTP scores and the CST scores. A quasi-experimental, nonequivalent control group design was used for 3 other designs to determine whether student participation in JEMP increased student math achievement in Pre-Algebra and Algebra. The dependent variable was the post-CST, and the two independent variables were treatment and gender, with the covariate being the previous CST scores. The results revealed a positive relationship between the grade 7 Pre-Algebra CST and the Pre-Algebra MDTP, and between the Algebra CST and the Algebra MDTP. Students who participated in JEMP performed significantly better in future math courses than their counterparts who did not participate in JEMP. Although not statistically significant, the results showed that students who participated in JEMP for 2 consecutive summers had higher mean grade 8 Algebra CST scores than those students who received only 1 treatment. Results of this study will be disseminated to other local school districts to help them improve their student math achievement. Study results will also be used to revamp and restructure JEMP's curriculum and pedagogy to make them more relevant to the new Common Core math standards. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2022 APA, all rights reserved)
