AB  - Colleges and universities are experiencing increasing concerns about the academic readiness of entrants who have just completed high school. Such concerns are especially common at our community colleges where open-door admissions policies tend to attract a larger percentage of less prepared students. This study investigated a teaching strategy that might raise the level of student achievement in high school mathematics. The participants in this research consisted of high school juniors and seniors; two Advanced Math Analysis classes, a Pre-Calculus, and an Algebra II class. This research sought to determine if the external control stimuli of frequent unannounced quizzes would effect student achievement on unit tests. Quizzes were administered two to three times a week to two of the classes while the traditional lecture/test model was used with the other two classes. Each quiz administered lasted from ten to fifteen minutes and consisted of problems similar to those appearing on the previous nights' homework assignment. In addition to quizzes, a unit test was given every other week. Grading periods when frequent quizzing was employed as the teaching strategy were rotated with grading periods when quizzes were not given. At the end of four rotated grading periods the mean unit test scores achieved during the grading periods when the quizzes were administered were compared to the mean unit test scores achieved during the non-quizzing periods. For this research, the Wilcoxon Signed-Ranks Test for paired data was selected to test the null hypothesis that no difference would be found in achievement levels during the quizzing vs. non-quizzing grading periods. A .05 level of significance was used for alpha. Students from the highly motivated Advanced Analysis classes achieved higher on their mean unit test scores when quizzes were administered, but students in the Pre-Calculus class and the Algebra 2 class showed no gain. The researcher concluded that frequent quizzing was effective in raising students' achievement levels in mathematics for those students who were already competitive and focused on high achievement. However, for students in classes that were less motivated and less focused on achievement, quizzing had no effect whatsoever on unit test performance.
