AB  - Despite high promise and calls for increased use, instructional technology has unrealized potential to support students in making sense of K-12 mathematics. This dissertation reports on studies of three instructional technologies, connected through themes of technology mediated formative assessment to support productive mathematical activity. Technology mediated formative assessment is presented as a reconceptualization of formative assessment were technology acts as a direct and indirect agent of formative assessment, gathering information on student learning and using that information to inform teacher decision making and/or the instruction of students. The first study reports on the design and effectiveness of an adaptive digital tutor for fractions instruction. The tutor acts as an agent of formative assessment, providing procedural and task feedback directly to students. This feedback comes from adaptive instruction based on student responses, procedural feedback based on patterns in student work, and dynamic feedback through digital manipulatives. A randomized crossover trial finds that a 2-week intervention with this software led to significant increases in student performance on fraction assessments. The second study reports on a mixed-methods study on how the classroom practices of two middle school teachers were impacted by incorporating interactive simulations and accompanying lesson plans into their teaching. Analyses of classroom video found significant increase in teacher use of student ideas, opportunities for students to explain mathematics, student critical questioning, and student mathematical discourse for both teachers when using the simulation lesson plans. Teacher interviews help explain how these shifts in practice occurred. The third study reports on parallel case studies of teachers using student response systems for formative assessment in high school algebra classrooms. Unlike other student response systems, Woot Math Formative Assessment allows students to submit work for their responses. The case studies reveal how this tool was used during individual and small-group formative assessment activities to support teachers in their use of student ideas, facilitation of productive discourse and use of feedback. The three studies provide complementary perspectives on how different instructional technologies can mediate the formative assessment process. Studies provide insight into how instructional technology can support both students and teachers in K-12 mathematics classrooms.
