AB  - The purpose of this quantitative causal-comparative study was to examine if and to what extent statistically significant differences existed between CDT formative assessment adopters and CDT formative assessment non-adopters in reading and mathematics achievement of Title I grade 8 as measured by the 2011 to 2012 change in school-level PSSA performance in urban Pennsylvania. Bloom's mastery learning theory underpins the adoption of CDT for formative assessment and learning outcomes of school-level achievement. The two research questions asked whether statistically significant differences existed between CDT formative assessment adopters and non-adopters in reading achievement (or mathematics achievement) of Title I middle school grade 8 as measured by the change in school-level PSSA performance. Upon outlier exclusion, the final study sample was 189 eligible Title I schools (n1 = 61, n2 = 128). The sample represented 25.33% of the target population of 746 consecutive eligible status Title I schools containing grade 8 in Pennsylvania. Results of two independent samples t-test at 0.05 significance level showed no statistical significant difference among CDT adopters and non-adopters in terms of Delta_Reading, t(187) = -0.81, p = .419, and Delta_Math, t(187) = -0.96, p = .339. As districts adopt technology-based programs to aid in school-level achievement, the impact of school-wide adoption, and the influence of school climate on student motivation and closing the achievement gap needs further study. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2020 APA, all rights reserved)
