AB  - Formative assessment is important for improving student learning in all classrooms and can be easily facilitated in large classes by personal response systems (clickers). A critical component of formative assessment is the feedback associated with it. Therefore, the objective of this study was to identify the amount of feedback that is critical and sufficient to improve student exam performance. To address this goal, a mixed methods approach was employed to examine how students performed on course exams in relation to the use of low-, mid-, and high-level clicker questions asked in class, as well as the detail of feedback they received immediately following each class. Low-level questions included fact-based and comprehension questions, mid-level questions involved the application of concepts, and high-level questions included analysis of data and evaluation of arguments. The results showed that while students appreciate the preparation for exam questions afforded by the clicker questions, there is no simple correlation in students’ performance between the difficulty of the clicker and exam questions. Furthermore, the feedback given to students did not have any statistically significant effect on their exam performance. Many limitations and confounding factors may have inhibited the significance in these results, including changes in the instructor’s in-class feedback for the clicker questions and dilution of the effect of the feedback and clicker questions by all of the other study materials provided to students. Implications regarding the relationship between the level of difficulty of clicker questions asked in class versus the exam, as well as suggestions for providing immediate but varied feedback are discussed.
