AB  - The purpose of this study was to investigate the effectiveness of formative standards-based assessments on learning in a mathematics classroom. This study looked particularly at the ways in which ongoing formative assessments could be used to inform a teacher about the learning of students in their classroom, as well as the instructional decision-making made based on the outcomes of those assessments. Using frequent and ongoing formative standards-based assessments, this study tracked the performance of learners in four eighth grade classrooms to answer the following questions:(1)How does a middle school math teacher use daily formative assessments aligned to standards to identify and support gaps in student learning and communicate progress to students?(2)In what ways does a middle school math teacher use a daily formative standards-based assessment to adjust practice?Using state standardized testing scores from the prior two years (SY 2017-18 and 2018-19), a pre- and posttest, as well as daily formative standards-based assessments, the researcher quantitatively tracked the levels of student learning for 65 students over the course of one unit of study in the 2019-2020 school year. The study did produce evidence of improved student learning among a subgroup of students who had previously shown to be making less than grade-level progress, as well as providing direction for educators in adjusting practice driven by data gathered from formative standards-based assessments. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2022 APA, all rights reserved)
