AB  - This study sought to determine the significance of Curriculum Based Assessment (CBA) with respect to its affect on achievement and specific classroom behaviors of high school students in general mathematics classes. Thirty low achieving students were subjectively identified by the teachers participating in the study and assigned to matched pairs. Group A received CBA interventions while Group B continued with traditional instruction. Achievement was measured by teacher grades, a standardized measure (Stanford Test of Academic Skills), and the Nevada State Mathematics Proficiency Examination. Classroom behaviors were rated by independent observers measuring time on task, tasks completed, and tasks comprehended. Two classrooms constituted the treatment/control settings in which four classes were taught by two teachers at different times during the regular school day. The only difference was that the experimental group received the CBA learning packets. Findings indicated that there was clear statistical evidence supporting greater improvement in the experimental group than in the control group in terms of teacher grades and task completion efforts. For the Nevada State Mathematics Proficiency Examination and the Standford Test of Academic Skills, both groups experienced statistically significant gains from pretest to posttest results. There were no significant differences in gain scores, however, between the groups. In terms of on-task and task comprehension, it was found that there was no significant difference between groups on these two variables. From the matched pair analysis, it should be noted that in general, more subjects in the experimental group performed better than their counterparts in the control group for all six variables. This pattern was even evident for variables in which there was no statistically significant difference between groups.
