AB  - This study investigated the effects of a criterion-referenced model of curriculum-based assessment (CBA) on the rates of social studies skill acquisition in secondary level students with learning disabilities. CBA was implemented with six students, aged 12-14 years, across two academic tasks: locating countries on a blank map and matching the names of countries with their capital cities. A multiple baseline design was used, and the order in which CBA was implemented across the two tasks was counterbalanced to control for sequence effects. During the experimental phase, students set outcome goals, constructed their own graphs, and plotted their daily scores on graphs. The results of the study indicated that CBA increased students' rates of skill acquisition for both of the academic tasks, but this was true only when students mastered the skill of locating countries prior to attempting to match the names of countries with capital cities. When students attempted to master the matching task without first mastering the map location task, they were not successful. The findings corroborated previous research regarding the use of CBA for increasing student achievement. CBA was shown to be a robust technique through its successful use with a new population (secondary level students with learning disabilities). The CBA methodology also proved to have a motivating effect on students. Implications for theory included support for CBA as an effective teaching behavior that provides for student success through the establishment of optimal conditions for learning. Research implications included the difficulty of conducting formative evaluation on a daily basis, and an alternative schedule was recommended. Practical implications included the efficacy of CBA in measuring performance in social studies, the appropriateness of using a criterion-referenced model of CBA in social studies, the importance of empirically supported skill sequences, and the relevance of CBA to both general and special educators.
