AB  - The quantitative study with a quasi-experimental design was conducted at a comprehensive high school to determine if a relationship could exist between the formative use of assessment and academic progress toward pre-determined learning objectives based on state standards. Academic progress toward learning objectives based on assessment results used formatively was compared to academic progress on assessment results used summatively. The sample population of convenience consisted of sophomore students from college-preparatory classes in world history. Formative assessment results from the experimental group were compared to assessment results used summatively from the control group. Teachers and students in the treatment group were provided specific feedback and assessment result analyses while participants in the control group were provided only assessment results. Statistical analyses of assessment results between assessment events and groups indicated that no statistically significant difference existed between the treatment and control groups. Limitations and implications derived from the study are discussed including the need to examine other aspects of the classroom environment that contribute to teaching and learning behaviors. Recommendations for further study on assessment data used formatively are presented.
