AB  - Given the importance of high-quality early literacy programs informed by ongoing and systematic assessment approaches for young English Language Learners (ELL) with disabilities, the study was designed to test the effectiveness of teachers using Curriculum-Based Decision Making (CBDM). In CBDM, teachers weekly assessed children's performance, made instructional adaptations based on the data, and evaluated the effects of instructional changes. CBDM was designed to enhance teachers' instructional planning and children's learning. Participants were 291 preschoolers and 17 teachers participating in an Early Reading First project where a validated, intensive, and structured early literacy program was being implemented. Teachers were assigned one of three groups: CBDM (CBM plus decision making guidelines), CBM-only, and no CBM (control). The number of children in each group was 53, 52, and 186 respectively. Children's progress in acquiring early literacy skills was evaluated using standardized measures of early literacy and class-wide applications of CBM. Results indicated significant group differences favoring the CBDM Group on posttests of early literacy measures. Both High- and Low-Risk Groups in the CBDM condition demonstrated significantly greater improvements on more posttests than groups in the CBM condition. In addition, both High- and Low-Risk Groups in the CBDM condition showed superior performance relative to the groups in the CBM condition even after pretest scores and language proficiency were controlled. As hypothesized, CBDM made a distinct contribution to the acquisition of early literacy skills of preschool ELL with and without special needs. Results support the systematic and structured evaluation of CBM data rather than unsystematic teacher inspection of CBM data for formulating decisions concerning the adequacy of instructional programs. The significant progress demonstrated by ELL with special needs and at-risk suggests that CBDM should be an integral component of preschool programs. Limitations and implications for practice are discussed.
