AB  - Current trends in mathematics instruction delivery methods show an increase in the integration of face-to-face instruction with online course management systems (OCMA) and paper-and-pencil methods as learning media. The evidence on the impact of OCMA use on students' mathematics performance, satisfaction, and achievement is inconclusive. The focus of this quasi-experimental two-group comparison quantitative research was to investigate if there is a difference in mathematics performance, satisfaction, and achievement between middle school students using OCMA and those of their peers who used paper-and-pencil methods. Fifty-seven 6th grade students from a medium-size urban middle school located in the southern region of the United States took part in this study. A pretest, posttest, and satisfaction questionnaire were administered in print format and students' responses were completed using paper-and-pencil methods. The treatment consisted of four weekly mathematics assessments administered via OCMA and reflecting concurrent mathematics content instruction. The responses to these assessments provided the data for statistical analysis using ANCOVA to control for students' mathematics ability. The results showed that there is statistically significant evidence that the use of OCMA in 6 th grade mathematics increased students' performance, there is statistically significant evidence that the use of OCMA in 6th grade mathematics increased students' satisfaction, and that there is no statistically significant evidence that the use of OCMA in 6th mathematics increased students' achievement. Research is needed to elucidate the effects of OCMA use on mathematics achievement as OCMA use was identified as an influential but not statistically significant factor in explaining mathematics achievement. Further research on the impact of OCMA use in K-12 mathematics education on students' performance, satisfaction, and achievement is needed to clarify inconsistent evidence found in the literature. Research on the effects of OCMA use in K-12 mathematics education on students' conceptual understanding, skills mastery, and content retention is needed as relatively few studies have been conducted in these areas. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2022 APA, all rights reserved)
