AB  - The present study investigated the impact of an integrated learning system (ILS) on student performance. Specifically, the WICAT ILS was evaluated through traditional and curriculum-based procedures. Students (N = 600) from a suburban southwestern school district participated in the study. Students were administered a pre-test in reading and mathematics through the WICAT system. Students received WICAT instruction three times per week in 45 minute sessions for seven weeks at the beginning of the school year. At the end of the seven week period, students received a post-test in reading and mathematics presented on the WICAT system. Student performance was examined with regard to sex, grade, socioeconomic status, academic subject, and educational program. Using a ANCOVA, significant differences were identified across grade, SES, and type of educational program. First and fourth grade students performed significantly higher on the post-test than second, third, and seventh graders. Significant grade differences were also demonstrated in slope of daily WICAT mastery tests. Students who were from lower SES backgrounds mastered more skills on the post-test than students from higher SES backgrounds. Similarly, students receiving special education services obtained higher post-test percentages than regular education students. Implications were discussed in terms of educational importance and future research.
