AB  - Sound classroom assessment requires meaningful grades. Yet often grades are impossible to interpret. Traditional assessment and grading practices can leave students unclear about what skills they need to improve on and lack detail. Further, compounding these issues is that often students cannot attempt to improve the skills. Often teachers teach to a topic instead of an ability to be honed. At Jeff Tech, we have seen the power of teaching a skill, providing feedback, and allowing a student to show mastery in Career and Technical (CTE) classrooms. Students internalize expectations that they can and will be able to master the necessary skills and demonstrate that mastery. Curriculum in all areas is broken into a set of skills. Students are assessed using formative and summative means on each skill and attempt a skill multiple times with a variety of assessments and differentiation. The goal is for a student to master a task, not simply to assign a number value to their attempt or to assess what they are capable of in the moment. This study examined the effectiveness of the school-wide competency based grading platform at Jeff Tech. Student performance on the Keystone Exams in Mathematics were evaluated for growth. The Algebra 1 classes were evaluated for the final grades of students and the passing rates. Data aided in determining the success of the program. The implications in this study can be used to determine the level of ongoing commitment that each stakeholder should have towards the initiative. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2022 APA, all rights reserved)
