AB  - The purpose of this study is to look at the literature on the effect of frequent testing on academic achievement from a meta-analytic perspective. For this purpose, a broad literature review was conducted and after the studies were reviewed and inclusion criteria were applied, 78 experimental or quasi-experimental studies on the effectiveness of academic achievement were selected as the final study sample. Although methodologies and designs of the studies varied, they all searched whether delivering frequent classroom tests would make a difference on academic achievement on a later on a final exam. Finding the overall effect size for the studies on the effectiveness of frequent testing was the main research question. Besides this, many study characteristics formed the additional research questions. For Example, the study looked at if using the same or different instructors to teach the experimental and control groups would make a difference on the achievement, whether there was a difference between studies of frequent testing on college level and high school level, whether offering feedback only to the experimental group would influence the results and more methodological and study characteristics that might influence the results are formed the additional research questions. Results indicate that frequent testing increases academic achievement by 0.43 standard deviation. This is an almost medium effect size according to Cohen's criteria. Although the overall affect size is almost medium in the size, most of the moderator variables that were thought to be related to frequent testing did not found to be significant. Only significant difference is found between the studies coming from different publication sources and between the published and not published studies. According to results, journal articles had a large mean effect size value as it was expected. Again not surprisingly published studies had a large mean effect size. The major implication this study provides is for the future researcher of frequent testing. The study searches in dept the characteristics of frequent testing studies, that way it is easier for future researchers of frequent testing to see the major design mistakes and prevent them from happening in their designs.
