AB  - The purpose of this study was to examine the effects of a novel research-supported testing method called The SPARK (Spiraling Assessment to Reinforce Knowledge) Testing Method on 8th-grade students' end-of-course (EOC) test scores in algebra I. An overview of relevant learning theories and inconsistencies between these theories and classroom assessments was described. A quasi-experimental pretest-posttest design was used to address the research question. A total of 284 EOC algebra I test scores were obtained from the math facilitator of a large urban school district. EOC test scores were analyzed to determine the means and standard deviations of students assessed by a SPARK teacher and those assessed by seven non-SPARK teachers. The students' Iowa Assessment math standard scores (M1314) from the year prior to taking algebra I were used as the covariate to account for incoming differences in math achievement. An ANCOVA was used to examine differences in EOC means adjusted for prior math achievement between students assessed by the SPARK teacher and the non-SPARK teachers. The results showed that students assessed by the SPARK teacher on average performed as well as or better than students assessed by non-SPARK teachers. Effect sizes for statistically significant mean differences between SPARK and non-SPARK teachers ranged from medium to large. Within the discussion section, a strong case was made for linkages between the SPARK method and instruction aligned with learning theories related to cognitivism and constructivism. Overall findings and restriction of this study to one subject area and grade level emphasize that further research is needed into the effectiveness of the SPARK testing method to understand the role of weekly, cumulative, and comprehensive assessment formats on student learning across disciplines and age groups. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2022 APA, all rights reserved)
