AB  - In this mixed-method, applied research study, the researcher attempted to increase the skills of the students and the teachers to increase the number of sixth-grade students who would score proficient or advanced on the MAAP’s end-of-year assessment. An increased number of proficient sixth-grade mathematics students improves proficiency throughout middle and secondary schools, and it improves college and career readiness. Furthermore, an increase in proficient sixth-grade students improves individual lives and community economics. In this study, the researcher used curriculum-based measurement (CBM) formative assessments to track students’ performance and to drive the teacher’s instruction. The research study was performed at a middle school in northwest Mississippi in the classroom of a sixth-grade mathematics teacher. Discrete, quantitative statistics were used to analyze the students’ academic performance before, during, and after the CBM progress-monitoring implementation. The data from the teacher instructional adaptability and responsiveness to the students’ specific academic needs were analyzed before and after implementing CBM progress monitoring. The action plan was focused on student progress monitoring with appropriate correctives and feedback implemented as dictated by the process data and the decision model. Instructional changes were monitored for appropriateness and effectiveness. Program evaluation data were collected from formative, interim, and summative assessments. Teacher interviews, pre- and postobservation of classroom conferences, and classroom observations provided qualitative data and insights. Findings were reported according to output data when answering the research questions.
