AB  - Since the Soviet launch of Sputnik, the United States has been concerned with competing globally in science and mathematics. In 1958, the National Defense Education Act was passed to raise national academic achievement. Since 1969, to ensure students were performing at acceptable levels, Basic-Skills and End Of Course (EOC) tests have been employed in schools in most states. District and campus accountability, student promotion, and funding are often tied to student performance on these tests. Since 2012,the State of Texas Assessments of Academic Readiness (STAAR) has been the assessment for Texas. Concerned with improving STAAR performance, many teachers administer frequent formative exams as a means of increasing student familiarity with subject matter and testing techniques. Some researchers have suggested means by which formative assessment effectiveness might be enhanced. However, a gap in the literature was found concerning formative assessment effectiveness relative to the number of tests given. The current study intended to fill that gap. Utilizing historical data on common formative assessments (CFA) and campus scores on the 2016-2017 fourth grade mathematics STAAR, this study employed a one-way between subjects ANOVA to determine the relationship between student performance and increments of formative assessments administered. Clusters of five to eight, nine to 14, and 15 or more formative assessments administered prior to the STAAR were examined. The findings of the current study showed that the number of CFAs administered did not influence student performance, either at the campus level or across campuses in one north Texas independent school district. All campuses in the current study met the STAAR passing standard, regardless of the number of CFAs that were administered. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2022 APA, all rights reserved)
