AB  - Colorado's 2009 Education Accountability law dictates that schools failing to demonstrate expected student outcomes for five consecutive years may face sanctions that include school closure, chartering, privatization, and the firing of school personnel. District turnaround policy makers are tasked to identify the most effective improvement strategies. Research on the use of interim assessment to increase student outcomes has been inconclusive regarding whether implementation costs are worth the benefit. Policy makers have continued to implement interim assessment as part of school improvement in schools identified as priority improvement and turnaround without research to guide practice. Using Production Function Theory as a conceptual framework, this quantitative, quasi-experimental study included 23 priority improvement and turnaround schools that used interim assessment as part of school improvement from 2011--2014. The study was used to determine the extent to which IA implementation positively affected student growth percentiles in the areas of reading and math. For reading, the findings were a statistically significant increase in mean MGP with a moderate effect size. For math, the findings were an increase in mean MGP that was not statistically significant with a small effect size. Two conclusions were drawn from these findings: (1) the use of interim assessment to support improved reading instruction is justifiable for policy makers seeking to support strategies for increasing student growth in reading and (2) policy makers should conduct a 'health check' on foundational areas of math instruction prior to math interim assessment implementation. Three recommendations for future research are (1) a quantitative study focused on student growth percentiles for historically disadvantaged groups of students to determine if the use of interim assessment supported closing the achievement gap, (2) a qualitative study focused on the use data literacy to support policy makers in determining appropriate foundational support and training prior to deploying interim assessment within school improvement strategy, and (3) mixed methods research to first identify which interim assessments are utilized in turnaround schools that show increased growth and second, to study teacher perception of these tools in relation to increases in student growth. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2022 APA, all rights reserved)
