AB  - Standardized norm-referenced tests have dominated the field of educational assessment for years. Many educators recognized, though, that standardized norm-referenced tests lacked adequate psychometric characteristics and also lacked instructional relevance. In order to deal with these inadequacies, educators developed curriculum-based assessment as an alternative to standardized, norm-referenced tests. In curriculum-based assessment, teachers observe and record student performance in the local curriculum. Research revealed that the use of curriculum-based assessment led to improvements in student academic performance and teacher instructional behavior. However, curriculum-based assessment is a complex process and consists of a variety of components, such as the provision of feedback to students and teachers and the provision of remediation recommendations to teachers. Any one or group of components might influence students and teachers to change their behavior. The purpose of the present study was to determine the influence of five components of curriculum-based assessment on student academic performance and on teacher instructional behavior. In a multiple-baseline design across groups of subjects, the researcher in the present study sequentially administered each of five components of curriculum-based assessment to groups of two or three students. Although the participating teachers claimed that their understanding of their students' academic difficulties improved, none of the components had consistent positive effects on students' or teachers' behaviors. Varying levels of motivation of the subjects inhibited improvements in student and teacher behaviors. Other problems encountered in the study, such as distinguishing practice and motivation effects from the effects of components and assessing reading comprehension accurately, frequently prevented the determination of the effects of the components of curriculum-based assessment on the dependent measures. In spite of the problems encountered in this study, certain components of curriculum-based assessment did exert some influence on the academic performance of some students and the instructional behavior of the teachers. Whether any component can be a powerful independent variable with noticeable influence on a variety of behaviors of many students and teachers is an issue for future research.
