AB  - Studied reasons for why many high school students experience serious learning difficulties in physics in the context of an introductory (9th grade) physics course offered in Israeli high schools. Following a detailed task analysis, the cognitive entry requirements for the course were identified, and students were tested for them. Specific difficulties students encountered during the course and prevailing misconceptions were identified. Based on this information, a remedial teaching method was developed. It consisted of supplying students with immediate and frequent feedback to reinforce their understanding, correct misunderstandings, and fill in gaps in background skills, while teachers continuously monitored the progress of each student. The process took place within the natural classroom setting, without additional staff or time requirements. The method was implemented in a large number of schools, and its impact was assessed using an experimental vs control ANCOVA design. Achievement of the experimental group (38 students) was significantly higher than that of the control group (48 students). The statistical analysis used students' background as the covariate. Of the 47% of the variance that the model accounted for, 24% was explained by the covariate (background) and 16% by the effect of the treatment; both were highly significant. An additional 7% was the teachers' effect (nested within treatments), but this effect did not reach significance. (24 ref) (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2022 APA, all rights reserved)
