AB  - In numerous component analyses of F. S. Keller's (see record [rid]1969-04532-001[/rid]) Personalized System of Instruction (PSI), educational researchers have systematically varied features of personalized instruction and observed the effects of their manipulations on instructional outcomes. The present paper discusses the methodology and reviews the results of these component analyses. The review demonstrates the importance for effective instruction of at least 4 PSI features: frequent quizzing, immediate feedback, a mastery requirement, and review units or items. The review suggests that students learn and retain more in PSI classes when (a) their progress is frequently evaluated on brief quizzes, (b) they receive feedback immediately after each assessment, (c) they are required to redo work until mastery is achieved, and (d) they are evaluated on review tests as well as after original learning. (58 ref) (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
