AB  - The focus of this research was to examine instructional methods and programs that have the potential of closing the achievement gap for children who did not experience rich oral language development in the early years. The study was conducted in an inner-city, high poverty school, with a high percentage of second language learners (88%), while they were implementing a new reading program with a strong oral language component. This increased focus on vocabulary has shown statistically significant gains in reading achievement as measured by the MCAS. This study began in the spring of 2010 with grade three students when the new reading program was being implemented. Both third grade classes showed statistically significant gains in vocabulary growth, as well as in over-all reading achievement. These data agree with the current research, which suggests that the increased time and emphasis on vocabulary development can have a positive effect on reading achievement. During the second year of the study, half of the original study group (now in grade four) received vocabulary instruction using additional research based strategies, combined with the new reading program. The other half of the study participants (control group) received instruction using the new reading program alone. The experimental group made significant gains over the control group in reading achievement. In addition to analyzing test scores to determine gains in reading achievement, qualitative data was collected on the fidelity of the implementation of the new reading program, as well as the frequency of strategies used and amount of time spent on vocabulary development. This data was collected through classroom observations and conversations with the classroom teachers involved in the study. The implications for practice are evident. It is not just the need for increased time spent on vocabulary development, but the quality of instructional practices that must be improved, as well. (PsycInfo Datab