AB  - The present study examined the ability of curriculum-based dynamic assessment that emphasizes a triarchic model of intelligence to reveal learning potential and developing expertise in a classroom setting compared to ability revealed by classic paper and pencil tests. While a large body of research points to the effectiveness of dynamic assessment as an alternative to classic intelligence tests in terms of its ability to demonstrate hidden expertise, there is a dearth of research on its utility as an alternative curriculum-based measure in classroom settings. In addition, the present study examined the impact of triarchic instruction, alone and in conjunction with dynamic assessment, over classic classroom instruction on students' performance on standardized achievement tests. This was a field study of 248 participants that compared three study groups, each composed of regular education fourth grade students from tri-state area public schools. Results indicated that dynamic assessment was effective in helping students demonstrate expertise over studied classroom material compared to peers who were required to demonstrate their expertise through paper and pencil tests. Further, in contrast to static assessment, dynamic assessment helped students who performed poorly on a baseline math achievement test show equal expertise over classroom material as their peers who did well on the achievement test. Finally, results indicated that triarchic instruction itself significantly improved students' performance on standardized tests over classic instruction. This was a pioneer study bridging the theory and research on dynamic assessment to the body of research on strategies for best practices in classroom instruction and assessment. In bridging these two areas, it further linked psychological theory with educational practice, and provided nuanced findings that contribute to clinicians' and educators' understanding of learning processes and learning potential. The findings in this study provide clinicians and educators with effective strategies for recognizing latent potential in underachieving students, and access to the instruction and assessment tools that can help those students demonstrate greater ability. Most importantly, this research provides students currently at risk of academic failure and the damaging psychological and social consequences that can result, hope of present and future academic success. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2022 APA, all rights reserved)
