AB  - The passage of the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA, 2004) has brought considerable support in law for the use of a response-to-intervention (RTI) process utilizing an array of scientific and researched-based procedures to determine if and how students respond to specific changes in instruction. RTI is often used within a problem-solving model to identify effective instructional or intervention strategies and to evaluate their effectiveness. An essential component of problem-solving and evidence-based practices is the use of progress-monitoring data to inform and guide educational decision making. Consistent with best practice, the use of highly structured, precise, and empirically validated progress-monitoring procedures can lead to improved student outcomes (Fuchs, 1986). However, progress-monitoring procedures are not typically developed or used for determining intervention effectiveness, or students' response to intervention. A major goal of this study was to determine the impact of training and the role of a structured problem-solving approach in promoting the quality of progress-monitoring procedures. A second purpose of this study was to examine the impact that the quality of progress-monitoring procedures had on student outcomes. Results indicate that participants who received training in the problem-solving process developed progress-monitoring procedures of higher overall quality as compared to control school participants. When examining the impact of training in problem solving and the quality of progress-monitoring procedures on the academic and behavioral outcomes of students, there were no statistically significant differences between the control and treatment schools. However, case-by-case examination of data showed more students in the treatment school to achieve greater progress as measured by goal attainment scaling (GAS). Students from the treatment school made greater academic and behavioral gains using GAS compared to rating scales. In comparison to prereferral teams at the treatment school developing behavioral goals, teams developing academic goals achieved relatively higher scores on the Progress-Monitoring Procedural Coding Scheme, and had more students make significant improvements toward academic goals as measured by GAS relative change scores. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2022 APA, all rights reserved)
