AB  - The use of personal technology devices such as cell phones to increase communication and productivity in the workplace has been common since the 1990s, but has been slow in moving to the classroom. The Bring Your Own Technology (BYOT) movement is part of an effort to more rapidly overcome the financial obstacle of providing individual devices for every student, often referred to as a one-to-one model of technology-aided learning, and at the same time to increase student engagement with the devices students are already using outside of school. Implementing online learning activities that engage students while collecting formative assessment data allows teachers to check understanding more efficiently and accurately. Obstacles to BYOT implementation in some schools are cost, extra time for teachers required to create online quizzes, and digital distraction becoming a hindrance to learning. This study sought to investigate the effectiveness of using BYOT to collect formative assessment data to increase student engagement and achievement. Mixed methods were selected for this study in order to assess the impact of using BYOT to administer formative assessments on student engagement and student achievement. The following research questions were explored: Is there a difference in student engagement between groups that use BYOT and groups that do not use BYOT for formative assessments? Is there a difference in student achievement between groups that use BYOT and groups that do not use BYOT for formative assessments? What are students' perceptions regarding the use of BYOT as a teaching and learning tool in the high-school setting? What are teachers' perceptions regarding the use of BYOT as a teaching and learning tool in the high-school setting? Based upon the literature review, the researcher hypothesized that formative assessments administered using BYOT would positively affect student engagement and student achievement. To investigate these questions, both quantitative and qualitative data were obtained through paper and electronically administered surveys as well as summative assessment test scores. The results of this study were positive for increasing student engagement as perceived by the students, but Student Engagement Instrument scores and unit test data found that BYOT could not be attributed to having a significant effect on student engagement and student achievement. Teacher perceptions were mixed regarding how effective the use of BYOT for formative assessments were. It did, however, collect insights into student and teacher perceptions about the use of BYOT for formative assessments. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2020 APA, all rights reserved)
