AB  - The primary purpose of this study was to investigate the effects of practice mode (recall and recognition) in computer-based instruction on immediate and delayed achievement. A total of 153 seventh-grade science students participated in the study. Subjects were blocked by sex and randomly assigned to one of two practice modes (recall and recognition) in an instructional program and to both an immediate and delayed test or a delayed-only test condition. The criterion test was a 30-item posttest consisting of 15 recall items and 15 recognition items. After completing the instructional program, subjects were given the choice of topic, practice mode, and delivery medium for a second program. Achievement data were analyzed using MANOVA with the two types of test items as the dependent measures. MANOVA yielded no significant differences for achievement by practice mode or sex, except for a significant univariate effect indicating that recall practice yielded higher scores than recognition practice on recognition items for subjects who took the delayed test only. A strong time of testing effect revealed that subjects who took the immediate posttest scored significantly higher on the delayed test than subjects who took the delayed test only. This effect was significant at the.0001 level for both recall and recognition test items. The attitudinal data revealed that subjects' choice of topics to study varied significantly depending on whether the instruction for the topic was available on the computer. Subjects reported a strong preference for recognition over recall practice in addition to their preference for computer-delivered instruction.
