AB  - The United States Department of Defense Dependents Schools-Germany adopted a single basal reading series including a management system involving periodic student skills mastery testing. Problem. Limited time was available for instruction and evaluation in reading. Criterion referenced skills mastery (magazine) tests were required periodically, but skills lesson tests used with every unit were optional. Purpose. The effect of differing assessment procedures on student achievement and its implications for the use of time and resources were the focus of this study. Procedures. The sample was eight second grade classroom units of teachers, only some of which used optional skills lesson tests. The different assessment procedures provided a natural experiment. Data were obtained from: structured teacher interviews; pupils' magazine test and standardized achievement test scores; attendance records; and sample lesson plans. The independent variable was the differing use of skills lesson tests. Reading achievement was the dependent variable and the factors which may have influenced it were control variables. Magazine test scores for comprehension, vocabulary, and phonetic analysis were compared for the groups experiencing different assessment procedures controlling for instruction level, chronological age, gender, and days absent. Findings. There were no statistically significant differences between the group that took skills lesson tests and the group that did not. Controlling for instruction level, chronological age, gender, and days absent also revealed no statistically significant differences. Conclusions. Different assessment procedures and time used do not affect students' reading achievement. Students apparently attain sufficient skills practice from instruction and workbooks. More testing was not better. Recommendations. Assessment testing should have a formative role in the reading program. Administrators, Reading Improvement Specialists, and teachers should be informed that giving skills lesson tests does not positively affect scores on magazines tests for second grade students. (Copies available exclusively from Micrographics Department, Doheny Library, USC, Los Angeles, CA 90089-0182.)
