AB  - Formative assessments, which should be ongoing assessments, are used to guide educators as students learn as opposed to those assessments, often described as summative, that are used to evaluate learning at the end of a teaching cycle. Formative assessments are being used by many large school districts to alleviate the pressure of passing the state mandated test. The 2002 passage of the No Child Left Behind Act holds all educators accountable for every child, regardless of socioeconomic status, English language proficiency, exceptionality, race, or ethnicity. The intent of this study was to determine the effectiveness of Renaissance Learning formative assessments with 3rd and 4th grade at-risk learners. The study used data from five schools in a large urban school district. All receive Title I funds to support their educational programs. All students in the treatment group benefited from having access to the same district-wide curriculum and time allocation for reading and mathematics. All teachers of students in the treatment group administered the same district-wide formative assessment given to all students, regardless of status, in grades three and four. All 3 rd and 4th grade students in the study were administered the scheduled district-wide formative assessment, which is developed by Renaissance Learning. The diagnostic (pretest) was administered in the fall; the cumulative (posttest) was administered five months later. After the posttest, both data sets were analyzed. This study provides information that reveals or suggests that at-risk students who engage in Renaissance Learning formative assessments achieve respectable academic gains in reading and mathematics and good preparation for the annual state mandated test. This successful use of formative assessment to improve student learning is vital for any diverse, urban school district with a large population of at-risk students.
