AB  - This study was conducted to determine if a decrease of cognitive load expectancy associated with weekly spelling assessment would result in better performance on outcome measures. The theoretical basis for this study is the Information Processing Theory of Cognitive Psychology, which proposes that the human brain has a limited capacity. Presently, there is a concern regarding the decline in spelling scores on standardized tests across the country. Educators and parents are interested in innovative techniques to provide an alternative to traditional spelling instruction that has been ineffective for decades. That is why spelling instruction was chosen as the academic interest in the present study. Twenty-seven fourth grade students volunteered to participate in the six-weeks study. The students were randomly assigned to three different groups and two of the three groups received spelling instruction. The light cognitive load with instruction condition received half the words on Monday and was tested on Wednesday. They received the remaining half of the list on Wednesday after a test on the first half and were tested on the second half of words on Friday. The heavy cognitive load with instruction condition received all the words on Monday and was given an assessment on Friday. The control group was also given the entire list on Monday for one weekly assessment on Friday. The two conditions that received instruction met three times each week for thirty minutes to receive instruction and assessments. The control group also met with the researcher but was left alone to study without help. Two hypotheses were proposed for this study and were evaluated with a Multivariate Analysis of Covariance (MANCOVA) and a priori orthogonal contrasts to evaluate differences among the groups. Additional follow up analyses were conducted using a sign test. The a priori orthogonal contrasts revealed no statistically significant difference among the three groups for the levels of the independent variables (i.e., cognitive load and Fernald). The results of the sign test revealed a statistically significant difference for the cognitive load variable but not the Fernald instruction variable. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2022 APA, all rights reserved)
