AB  - Over the past 15-20 years, research has indicated that teachers who utilize curriculum-based measurement (CBM) to make instructional changes in their students' programs when warranted by poor performance patterns effect greater overall achievement among their students than do teachers who neglect to use systematic progress monitoring procedures. Furthermore, special education teachers who engage in their own forms of progress monitoring appear to change instructional programs infrequently, if at all, over the course of the year. This investigation contributed to previous research by separating the effects of simply making instructional changes, not based on student performance data, from the effects of making instructional changes in accordance with CBM data. Thus, teachers' effectiveness when implementing instructional changes in response to individual CBM data was contrasted with their effectiveness when implementing the same instructional modifications with students whose progress was not monitored with CBM. Teachers selected 42 pairs of students with learning disabilities and emotional disturbances for participation in the 20-week study. Teachers monitored the mathematics performance of one student from each pair using CBM. Instructional decisions were based on this student's progress; however, teachers implemented the same instructional changes for both the CBM student and his or her partner. Two related purposes of the study were to examine the effects of computerized consultation and the effects of frequent measurement on student achievement. Consequently, half of the teachers received a form of computerized consultation for instructional decision making, and half of the partners engaged in CBM tasks, although their teachers never saw partner data. Results indicated that the CBM students performed significantly better than their partners whose instructional changes were not based on CBM data. However, no difference in achievement was noted between students whose teachers did or did not receive computerized instructional consultation. Similarly, frequent mathematics measurement failed to affect student achievement significantly.
