AB  - In the current climate of high-stakes testing in education, the academic achievement of students is the highest priority among American schools (NCLB, 2001; Education Alliance, 2005). However, student achievement is often dictated by performance on formal, summative assessments and state testing assessments rather than informal, formative assessments and progress as observed and evaluated by the teacher. As such, curriculum pacing guides often drive elementary classroom instruction as opposed to the pace of student learning. Consequently, it is necessary to evaluate the assessment methods of elementary students to provide them with opportunities for multiple attempts to master content. DuFour (2004) stated that the priority for teachers should not be just ensuring that students have been taught the content; they should be concerned with whether they have learned the material and can apply the skills. Recent discussion among scholars proposes that students be afforded the opportunity to continuously demonstrate their understanding of the content since most students do not learn at the same rate or through the same methods (Wormeli, 2006; Brookhart, 2004). Research shows that gender may impact learning (Gurian, 2001; Pomerantz et al., 1997) and that academic performance can differ by race (Brooks-Gunn, McLanahan, Rouse, 2005; Jencks, Phillips, 1998; Fordham, Ogbu, 1986). The multiple attempts at mastery philosophy is a school-wide assessment practice in which students have the opportunity to continuously prove their mastery through a variety of assessment formats, such as oral testing or adjusted test length. Students resubmit assignments and retake alternative assessments to improve their grades and demonstrate their understanding of the curriculum. Remediation must take place prior to any re-assessment so that students and teachers can work together to address learning obstacles. The teacher assigns an alternative assessment, or re-do, of the assignments or assessments previously submitted. This study assessed the impact of the multiple attempts at mastery philosophy' based on student performance on the Language Arts and Mathematics sections of the Palmetto Assessment of State Standards (PASS) exam. The PASS exam is administered at the end of each school year for students in grades 3-12. The target population for this study included 549 fifth-grade elementary students from an upstate school district in South Carolina. The study consisted of students at Elementary School TA, which utilized a traditional grading practice. Additionally, students from Elementary School MAAM were included in the study, where the multiple attempts at mastery philosophy was used. Nine research questions were addressed in this study: I. Is there a significant difference in Mathematic academic achievement between students who experienced multiple attempts at mastery than that of their peers who experienced traditional grading policies as assessed on the Palmetto Assessment of State Standards (PASS) exam? 2. Is there a significant difference in Language Arts academic achievement between students who experienced multiple attempts at mastery than that of their peers who experienced traditional grading policies as assessed on the Palmetto Assessment of State Standards (PASS) exam? 3. Is there a significant difference in the Mathematic Palmetto Assessment of State Standards (PASS) exam results of the male and female students who experienced multiple attempts at mastery and those who did not experience the multiple attempts at mastery philosophy 4. Is there a significant difference in the Language Arts Palmetto Assessment of State Standards (PASS) exam results of the male and female students who experienced multiple attempts at mastery and those who did not experience the multiple attempts at mastery philosophy? 5. Is there a significant difference in the Mathematic Palmetto Assessment of State Standards (PAS… (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2022 APA, al