AB  - The research on interim assessments is inconclusive (Goertz, Olah, & Riggan, 2009b). A confounding issue on the use of interim assessments is the use of commercially available interim assessments. The purpose of this quantitative, causal-comparative study was to determine the difference of language arts performance scores among middle school students from a southeastern U.S. school district. Two research questions framed the study. The first overarching question examined the difference in student performance when a district implements locally developed and aligned interim assessments, and the sub-question examined the performance of students of different ability levels. The study used the formative feedback system model as a conceptual framework (Halverson, Prichett, & Watson, 2007). A general linear model approach was used for a repeated measures analysis of covariance to determine if the use of interim assessments was statistically significant, while controlling for initial differences on control variables (Weisberg, 2014). The data included three years of Grades 6-8 language arts scale scores for a convenience sample of 2,037 students. Student absences, gender, socioeconomic status, English language learner status, exceptional student education status, teacher advanced degree status, and teacher experience were used as control variables. The results were positively statistically significant with a moderate effect size of .57, which translates to more than half a school year of growth (Coe, Kime, Nevill, & Coleman, 2013). The results contribute to the research on interim assessments, inform stakeholders on the efficacy of interim assessments, and inform educators on the best types of interim assessments. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2020 APA, all rights reserved)
