AB  - In response to federal and state legislation aimed at increasing student achievement through accountability of teachers and staff, many California school districts are in the process of defining student learning objectives and instituting procedures to evaluate these objectives in cost-effective ways. During 1978, the Santa Cruz City School District (SCCSD) initiated a process whereby teachers generated student objectives for their classes, and these objectives were coordinated with the district proficiencies required for graduation from eighth grade. Although many school districts have instated such criterion-referenced systems, few have evaluated the process by assessing student achievement. To determine the benefit of the criterion-referenced system to students in SCCSD, a formative evaluation study was conducted comparing standardized test scores of students in different years, prior to and after implementation of the system. The process of developing and measuring the learning objectives was carried out by teachers throughout the district in coordination with administrative staff members. Staff members provided support for the activities by giving inservice workshops on writing objectives and determining evaluative criteria. Teachers' annual performance evaluations were partially based upon how closely they came to achieving the learning objectives established for their classes. Standardized test scores (Comprehensive Test of Basic Skills) were collected for seventh and eighth grade students in one of the district junior high schools prior to and after the criterion-referenced system had been established. It was expected that pretest-posttest gains would be higher in the year after the system was implemented than the prior year. A second question in the study was whether the district developed proficiency tests correlated significantly with the CTBS scores, by way of validating the district tests. The results showed that, contrary to expectation, student achievement showed greater gains in the year prior to actual implementation of the system. There were also significant differences in achievement of boys and girls. This became an important factor since there was a greater proportion of girls in the year prior to establishing the criterion-referenced system. Since the confounding of gender with class year was unavoidable in the design of the study, conclusions were only tentative that the process of developing a criterion-referenced system was not advantageous to student achievement. It was suggested that a longitudinal study be conducted to look at effects of the system and to control for the imbalance in boys and girls during some school years. Given that greatest gains were seen in achievement during the year when the development of the process was underway, a likely conclusion is that the enthusiasm of teachers, resulting from involvement on a district-wide basis, impacted students more than the actual system of specifically defined and coordinated learning objectives. If this is so, a worthy recommendation is that the administration of SCCSD plan to use a similar format in future district problem-solving activities. The differences between boys and girls in the district could also become a focus of attention for administrators rather than accepted as a normal situation for students of this age. The correlation between the district-defined proficiency tests and the CTBS scores were significant although not so large in magnitude that substitution of one test for the other is warranted.
