AB  - Educational achievement matters for all students. To meet the challenges of rapidly changing global demands, students need to possess what are termed 21st-century skills: creativity, collaboration, critical thinking, and communication. A deep conceptual understanding and use of mathematical processes plays a part in being a 21st-century learner. This qualitative action research study sought to address local problems of practice that present barriers to acquisition of mathematical skills for all students. Specifically, the study sought to address the disconnect that existed at a school site between the predominant instructional methods employed by teachers and instructional practices that support students’ deep conceptual understanding of mathematics.Over the course of the 2018–2019 school year, teachers at the treatment site implemented changes in their instructional practices in mathematics. Teachers in Grades 4 through 6 incorporated the formative assessment process into their regular math instruction. At the end of the school year, student achievement data from the CAASPP summative mathematics exam, were collected and compared to the previous year’s exam to measure the impact the change may have had on student performance. The findings indicate that all grade levels showed an increase in the percentage of students scoring Level 3 (Standard Met) or Level 4 (Standard Exceeded). Not only did the overall population demonstrate an increase, but traditionally underserved groups within the population also showed improvement across all grades. To strengthen any claims based on the results of the treatment group’s data, a control group was used as a comparison. In short, the control group did not experience the same improvements as the treatment group.Since the intent of action research is to provide answers to problems of practice at the local level, the recommendations made target the school site and district level. Based on the study findings, three recommendations are made: First, based on the positive student achievement results, it is recommended staff at the treatment site continue to develop their understanding and use of the formative assessment process. Second, because the environment that led to less than effective teacher practices was not one that supported teachers as reflective practitioners, I recommend that leadership throughout the district work toward creating an environment that encourages and promotes reflective practice. Finally, because the culture in the district has been tainted by past practices involving data from high-stakes tests, my third recommendation is that district data discussions be designed and guided to support teachers’ understanding and use of the data with a goal of changing their mental models about assessment.
